The first virtual provider is coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech suppliers offer virtually all services, as they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe it won't be long to wait.
The fact that Czech mobile communications providers work among the most expensive in Europe at all, we have often reported on this on Mobil.cz.
This also confirmed the ČTÚ Telecommunications Authority, which drew attention to the fact that the price of text here is higher than the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of roaming charges, there is so likely to be a paradoxical situation - for some Czech mobile communications providers SMS will be cheaper from abroad than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a combat attack.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of well over 100 %.
The mobile service providers, on the other hand, like to scramble that there is an extremely high level of competition in the Czech market.
The chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) is often a member of Pavel Dvořák, who often said in the past that there was no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is likely that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a lot of opportunities (by the way, it would probably find hardly any frequencies).
But there is one more possibility - a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market brought a significant price reduction, to which the classic mobile service providers had to respond.
Before the entry into the market of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, there were similar voices in the UK as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you don't need to look for examples for a long time.
In February of this we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider succeeded in winning more than 100 thousand customers and thus ascending to the five largest supplier in the country.
The Penta financial group, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual providers is that one can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers normally stand out as low cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of mobileling in Poland shows, it may also be quite good to put on a non-clear target group.
This supplier is specifically aimed at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is hard to say whether a similar concept could be taken into account in Poland, as well as in the Czech Republic.
The press speaker of Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the perspective of the supply of services."
In the Czech Republic chanceless, the mobile service providers mean
It is almost certain, however, that if a virtual mobile service provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobileking.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look particularly hopeful.
There will be a market entry of mobileing in other countries in our region," says a phone call for mobile phone call.cz Jana Studničková, press speaker of the Penta financial group.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the present mobile communications providers in the Czech Republic are not specifically committed to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything they can to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
Their interest in launching a virtual mobile phone provider has long been shown by the group GTS Novera, who wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed-line, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this opportunity with all Czech mobile service providers.
With some of them we have already been able to achieve progress in negotiations," said the press speaker of the Pavel Kaidl group.
Maybe better times will come now.
Non-official information shows that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this point we do not assume that in the Czech Republic there is room for a full virtual provider.
The Czech market has major specificities compared to other markets.
So far, we have not yet addressed a subject with a complex and serious project in this field", says in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Srše paper from the Press Department of Telefónica O2.
Other providers also refer to the specifics of the Czech market.
The press speaker of T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with the statement of O2: "Until now we have not yet found a viable and beneficial project to which one could build further."
And she adds: "A virtual provider will hardly appear in the T-Mobile network until the end of the year.
At this point we must have had a concrete offer to think so in the short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "For negotiations with potential virtual providers, we are open, especially in the area of sharing costs and infrastructure.
This is precisely what we consider to be the best from the point of view of our customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - hand in hand with the providers
The approach of mobile service providers is easy to understand, another provider was more competitive, this would lead to falling prices and thus also to a fall in profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
That the suppliers can pull at a stroke when it comes to something also proves the long coming and forth about the origin of U:fon.
The strongest pressure towards ČTÚ went out from the company T-Mobile at the time when U:fon came onto the market.
This also demonstrates the publicly available information from the ČTÚ websites.
But now it is just U:fon as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market was recently strengthened by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile communications provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would impose high requirements on the market itself and, above all, its services."
However, in view of this approach by mobile service providers, the absolute interest of Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not just the attitude of ČTÚ, who unfortunately does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic, in contrast to the United Kingdom and other highly developed states.
It is exclusively owned by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
But this involved his typical attitude to this whole problem.
"The entry into the market of a virtual mobile phone provider would then be possible after a contract was concluded between a mobile phone provider and a virtual provider on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic providers," said Kristián Chalupa in his reply to our request from the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS.
Such a formulation would not be surprising by the representatives of the providers.
This is more than worrying by an authority representing consumer interests and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses its position on the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Foreignly, where virtual providers work normally, it can be observed that their entry into the market has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
However, it is likely that the pressure on the correct functioning of the market and a price reduction is not one of the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, the almost already touching harmony of the three mobile telephone providers, resulting from their reactions, is really shocking.
The question of whether this really is just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolute same fuel price at the petrol stations is certainly just a coincidence and the result of a hard competition.
"In this case, the Authority has not discovered any signs of a competitive action, and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way in the matter.
None of the suppliers has a dominant market position, so they also do not have the appropriate increased responsibility for their activities on the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile market for virtual providers are likely to be lacking from the Telecommunications Regulatory Authority," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, prepared by ČTÚ, after which telecommunications is a single market from the perspective of economic competition.
On such a market, no one of the Czech mobile telephone providers will of course have a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the consent of the network operator is always necessary for the entry into the market of a virtual provider.
And the mobile service provider - logically - has the monopoly for its network.
This means that in a certain segment it necessarily takes a dominant position.
But even if you do not go along with this argument, it should at least be a warning to the ÚOHS that three mobile service providers are strikingly similar.
In doing so, complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) prove that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The removal of responsibility for ČTÚ is then a fairly common trick in the telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distance itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the amendment to the Telecommunication Act recently adopted does not allow the extension of ČTÚ's competences to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know this too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's going to happen if no one looks at it.
Only the operation of any pseudovirtual provider, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but which are only partially public.
Usually it is companies operating in the field of multilevel marketing.
Mobile telephone services, for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company is acting towards the operator as a classic company expert, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he will then receive special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resales.
"If there should be cases that you describe, then it can be a violation of the contractual conditions that we will then deal with, which can lead to an end to cooperation with the corresponding society," replied Martina Kemrová to our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that this is not the case with those responsible for mobile communications providers.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies, it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such action.
Indeed, the activities of these companies do not lead to negligible profits, at the same time they are not affected by the actual official marketing, in contrast to the actual virtual providers.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, despite all, the services of these companies are used only by a very low percentage of customers.
Moreover, they must accept that the SIM card on their phone does not run on their name, so they cannot have full value as the normal customers of mobile phone providers."
This alone, however, would have to be at least strange to the ČTÚ.
There is also another question for the ÚOHS.
The mobile service providers close their eyes to such an approach, why do they lock themselves against a virtual provider?
It must be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competences to discover such activities, and if it does not, it does not have to satisfy itself with the statement of the providers, they do not know anything about them and their terms and conditions would prohibit them from doing so.
When Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been pointed out several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers brought a significant price decline in the various services.
Practically in all countries where virtual providers have been created, the classical providers have tried to prevent their origin from being practically more or less.
The arguments used by them were virtually identical - a market too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, the regulatory bodies at the very moment tried to protect the interests of mobile service providers, but those of their customers.
Whether it was through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created and then followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies all fall to the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot escape the impression that uncertainty in the competences in these cases is more than favourable.
But we don't throw the flint into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider appears soon, perhaps the Czech mobile market will start moving again.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile phone provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting other interested parties (to discriminate).
And finally the Czechs will no longer call more expensive than the rest of Europe.
