The Prague transport companies transport on Wednesday for the first time also on a chip
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, will enter the history of Prague's transport companies as a date when passengers will enter a subway, tram or bus that will carry an electronic coupon in the pocket instead of a paper ticket.
These can currently buy about a hundred thousand people who own the Chipcard Opencard.
The passengers can buy a 30-day, 90-day or an annual coupon (since from 1 January 2009) and simultaneously record it on their chip card, in the information centres and branches of the transport companies at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nadraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letőany, Kmobilisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The coupons have been available on the website of the transport companies www.dpp.cz since yesterday.
The service was used up to the afternoon hours by over four hundred customers.
Those who use Internet sales can really forget the output window at the subway stations, where they had to wait regularly in long queues for their paper driving licenses.
They buy the coupon over the Internet, it is played on the open card in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"There is also a switch with trained staff available to travellers in these places, which advises interested parties when buying the Internet and also plays the coupon on the map", says Martin Opatrný, spokesman for the project.
In addition to the libraries, the electronic coupons can also be played on the open card on self-service machines, which are installed in some subwayvestibules.
What do such machines look like?
They are red, reminding of ticket values, the passengers may have noticed them already in the subway stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"At present there are five of them in the city, but it is supposed to be eighty by the end of the year," Opatrný adds.
The coupon controls an automatic instead of the driver
The operation of the machines that will work from tomorrow's onwards is simple.
You just have to insert the chip card, and the previously purchased coupon plays itself.
The electronic coupons will apply from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburban trains and on the bus lines with the numbers 300 to 499, with which the inhabitants of the Central Bohemia region in particular reach the capital.
"In the trains that belong to the Prague integrated traffic, the train attendants have read equipment that allows them to check the validity of the coupons by time and zone," says Filip Drápal of the Ropid organization. This organization compiles the schedules for the Prague transport companies.
The suburban buses have ticket readers at the checkout at the driver.
When entering, the chip card not only needs to be shown by the driver, but the open card must be placed at a marked spot on the side of the checkout.
The driver thus controls the validity of the listed coupons.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the listed coupons, nothing is easier than asking the driver for this information," says Drápal.
A passenger who doesn't ride suburban buses and doesn't know when the coupon's validity ends can go to the automats, where the coupons are played on the card.
The information on the validity of its documents is displayed here on the display of the device.
