Discrimination - From the blood that became safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of her founding yesterday, and her president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to be pleased because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it regained public confidence, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, during the 1980s the national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross's blood donation were contaminated with the HI virus and hepatitis C virus.
In view of this drama and public dissatisfaction, in February 1994, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation conducted by Judge Horace Krever aimed at bringing light to the circumstances that had led to such tragedy and to draw up guidelines to prevent a further catastrophe of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still reluctant to deliver his report, at the time several provinces put a committee on the legs whose aim was to develop a new system for managing blood canned in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this task.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, who is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to provide the other provinces and the two territories.
`1998, when Hema-Quebec took up her work, hardly 38% of people had confidence in the blood-conservation system in Quebec, remembers Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Due to the enormous efforts to improve the safety of the blood cans and through the work in this field during the following years, we have regained public confidence," she says, before emphatically stressing that at the beginning of 2008 almost 94% of Quebec's population had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that 'trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its foundation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted according to the principle of caution.
At this time we experienced the occurrence of numerous cases of the human form of cattle insanity in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells this woman who has been in charge since the founding in 1998.
"And we didn't have the slightest idea whether this disease could be transmitted over the blood.
So we called on one of the main guidelines of the Krever and Gélineau reports, which says that exclusion measures are applied if one does not know this and if a disease only progresses slowly, as is obviously the case with the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Now, a few years ago, it was unquestionably proved that this disease is being transmitted over the blood.
Thus this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we used has quite a meaning.
In 1999 a much more precise technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which enable the presence of the virus itself directly in the donor's blood, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST made it possible to shorten the time of incubation, which takes place between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be proven by our techniques in blood, explains the specialist.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors might be infected without knowing it, and one could not recognize this, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmission of AIDS via blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is in danger of receiving blood infected with HIV.
In other words, it means distributing 12 million blood cans before someone is infected with HIV.
Since hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood cans each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case in which HIV was transmitted over a blood can.
I believe you can feel comfortable these days when you get a blood transfusion or write to restore health,' says the director of Hema-Quebec.
Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogens can get into the system.
Only last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on Réunion's island, which, as well as the West Nile virus, is transmitted by insects over the blood.
We need to monitor continuously', continues Dr. Décary, before she emphasizes that Hema-Quebec must also provide a sufficient supply in addition to a secure supply.
The need is increasing because the population is ageing.
As cancer control treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor network, which averages only 3% of Quebec's blood-donors.
In doing so, every healthy person who is 18 years or older and meets the criteria of fitness can donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of the people who provide their blood are not accepted, for example, because they are ill with AIDS or malaria, and those who have traveled to a country in which malaria is spread are excluded from the blood donation for one year.
With this 3% we manage to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies are very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It is hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all, to keep them and make them become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that you rarely find the time to spend an hour in blood donation,' regrets Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of 297 million dollars, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood canned but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eye apples and skin, which is used almost exclusively for severe burn injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before stored in Hema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec's only public cord blood bank.
In the umbilical cord, previously considered biomedical waste, there is rich blood on stem cells that can serve to treat severe diseases, such as leukaemia.
A few weeks ago we celebrated the deposit of our thousandth cord blood sample, and we plan to take more than a thousand each year.
`We should probably start to provide it for transplants at the beginning of next year', explains Dr. Décary, who describes this program of cord blood decline as very popular.
Many mothers are convinced not to have access to it, because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
