The psychology of surrendering - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, the buyers tend to spend more and therefore overvalue the auctioner.
Neurologists and economic researchers from New York University have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the Science magazine, people do not want to be beaten in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even higher prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
A group of volunteers should play Lotto while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the volunteers were examined using functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
At both games, the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of Striatum, a complex below the brainline, was measured in the case of losers of the auction, in which oversupply of the opponent plays an important role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-remuneration" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore considered that the price increase could be explained by the prevention of an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to support their thesis, the economists in the research group have also carried out investigations to track the money.
In this case, three groups should offer to one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their efforts.
Another group was also promised 15 dollars reward, in the event that they come out of the game as winners.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which was also lost in the event of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was therefore merely that the emphasis was on winning, while the other was on losing.
However, as evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the "losing"-group were prepared to do more than those in the control or "wine" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
In fact, the practices observed at auctions have only so far been justified by the joy of winning, or risk prevention.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so that we now have a third explanation" - said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When does the doctor check out?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because the patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver disease caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E, the digestive tract (for example through contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted by blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, divorce or saliva).
Travellers are recommended to have vaccination against the viruses A and B at any rate, against the virus C there is no vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A show up about two-three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and vomiting.
Afterwards the jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine dark, and the recovery can last up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die every year from hepatitis B, more severe diseases such as liver cancer and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only every tenth infected person is in medical treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: untreated liver cirrhosis and liver cancer may occur.
Most infected people don't even know about their disease, as the pathogen secretly destroys the liver cells - in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular inspection, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who have undergone blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated to be 200 million.
Since the disease can already be detected in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the home doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
Just in time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thus preventing the risk of infection and preventing the emergence of cancer.
September 30 is the world day of hepatitis, organised for the first time in 2004 of patient representations worldwide.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness of this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, their origin and the importance of early detection.
