The study was the first in a research project in which, in addition to scientists, philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university also participated.
In an attempt, a sparkling device was attached to the left hand to the test subjects, which gave off the electric shocks.
The participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: on the one hand, a picture of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and Leonardo da Vinci's "Dame with the Hermelin".
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary among the faithful would produce a kind of religious trance, while they chose the image of Vinci, because it was hardly distinguished from the other painting and felt as soothing.
The test subjects spent half an hour in a MRI scanner, and at this time they received a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages while either looking at the religious or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that they felt "in security" at the sight of the Mother of God, as if they were "anxious" and they felt "rest and peace".
