Intelligent car imitates the flight of Hummel
What would be the best method for developing new technologies to avoid accidents if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented in which the Nissan engineers of Hummeln were inspired in the creation of new systems that prevent accidents.
In cooperation with Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic system, which is controlled by robots, a mini car, equipped with the characteristics of the bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protection shield", said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The combined eye of the bee, which can be seen in every direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
To imitate the function of the combined eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled distanceometer.
This identifies obstacles to the BR23C in a 180-degree field within 2 metres, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision prevention process.
The obstacle is recorded in fractions of seconds, and the auto robot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees, by turning the tyres around the appropriate angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver is purely instinctive.
"If it weren't, the car robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshoyuki Andoh, head of the "Mobility Laboratory" and the auto robot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are still considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of the bees when they avoid other bees.
And this must end in the fraction of a second.
However, in contrast to the bees, the deviation can not be up, down, or even diagonal - it can only be two-dimensional, only in the direction of the reversibility of the tyres.
While the bees are open to infinitely many possibilities to avoid other bees, the researchers were able to use only the rotational movement, or acceleration and brake, in the car robot.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient, and therefore have a longer service life than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it is due to instinctive, intelligent response, and less to the processing of the data, and even less to the ability to store it.
This device only has to process some inputs per second and react accordingly to them.
It does not have to store it, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction using earlier maneuvers, so that it is constantly using only a handful of KB memory.
No gigabyte and megabyte heavy memories are needed.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate collision prevention technology, which, according to Nissan, will be in production within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by consciously directing the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the goal.
