Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historic cinemas
The historical cinemas close due to the favoured multiplex kinos.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This image of director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is happening at the moment in the major urban centres of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of the exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-sale complexes in the periphery, means long-term death for the one-saal cinema in the center. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also carries the traits of a cultural crime.
The most affected are historical places full of memories, "It's like losing a friend with whom you've put a piece of street full of emotions," said the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", who brought him the Oskar and the great prize of Cannes 20 years ago. It's about the history of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a cinema world that is probably lost forever.
The figures that the Anec, the Central Trade Association provides, speak a clear language: over the last five years, the vast amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; these are for the most part the cinemas in the big cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the most affected regions are the Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This testifies to the fact that the main accusations are the multiplex kinos, because they are precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy is leading the lists, 81 are both in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, the president of the Anec, "but it is useful that new structures also arise, but first of all the preservation of the already existing one, because locks a hall in the city, not all its regular customers are willing to visit a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here is still the lack of budget for the foundation of the trade union: the debt burden recorded by the state amounts to about 10 million euros.
It is a shame from the ethical-moral point of view that the government does not observe the existing laws.
In order to obtain the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros in the year would be necessary".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, due to the fears of the old cinemas, has decided to protect them through an agreement between the community and the Anec; it is the first agreement of this kind in Italy to protect and support traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
Among the planned measures are tax advantages for the cinema operators as well as benefits for the public in terms of local transport: it will be allowed to go to the traffic-limited areas of the centre and also to park at cheaper parking fees.
"It's an encouraging initiative," said Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will join our example and also design new concepts.
But certainly we also need a better audio and video equipment to be able to do something against the superpower of the multiplex rooms, because finally the audience is more demanding today.
The defense of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closing of the "supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to establish the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even if I had been playing with the thought for 10 years.
For 25 years I have lived in Rome; when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in the Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn to the side not to have to see the dust-covered posters.
